Sensitivity Analysis¶

Sensitivity analysis is part of the vulnerability analysis and is used to determine how much input variables contribute to the uncertainty of outputs. Sensitivity analysis is an important tool to understand how robust the model is in terms of how small input changes can affect the outputs. The SOBOL method is used in this project as it is an apt way of understanding how variables individually as well as collectively contribute to the uncertainty of the model. Lastly, Feature Scoring is also used as it visually contributes to this, as it shows the influences of uncertainties on the outcomes.

# Show  S1 (first order) and ST (total effects) of variable

Si_costs = sobol.analyze(problem, results_of_interest[0].to_numpy(), calc_second_order=True, print_to_console=True)

Si_filter_costs = {k:Si_costs[k] for k in ['ST','ST_conf','S1','S1_conf']}
Si_df_costs = pd.DataFrame(Si_filter_costs, index=problem['names'])

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1)

indices = Si_df_costs[['S1','ST']]
err = Si_df_costs[['S1_conf','ST_conf']]

indices.plot.bar(yerr=err.values.T,ax=ax)
fig.set_size_inches(16,12)
fig.subplots_adjust(bottom=0.3)
plt.title('SOBOL Analysis for Total Costs (base case)')
plt.savefig('SOBOL_Costs_BC.png')

Si_deaths = sobol.analyze(problem, results_of_interest_p[1].to_numpy(), calc_second_order=True, print_to_console=True)

Si_filter_deaths = {k:Si_deaths[k] for k in ['ST','ST_conf','S1','S1_conf']}
Si_df_deaths = pd.DataFrame(Si_filter_deaths, index=problem['names'])

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1)

indices = Si_df_deaths[['S1','ST']]
err = Si_df_deaths[['S1_conf','ST_conf']]

indices.plot.bar(yerr=err.values.T,ax=ax)
fig.set_size_inches(16,12)
fig.subplots_adjust(bottom=0.3)
plt.title('SOBOL Analysis for Total Expected Number of Deaths (policies)')
plt.savefig('SOBOL_Deaths_P.png')
plt.show()
